title: New energy for the 133-keV resonance in the 23Na(p,gamma)24Mg reaction and its impact on nucleosynthesis in globular clusters

23Na(p,gamma)24Mg reaction and its impact on
nucleosynthesis in globular clusters

x4freetext: The Triangle Universities Nuclear
Laboratory (TUNL) Enge split-pole spectrograph.
Targets were produced under vacuum by thermally
evaporating NaBr powder onto 22 mu-g/cm2-thick
natural carbon backing foils. The NaBr thickness, as
measured with a thickness monitor during evaporation,
was approximately 70 mu-g/cm2. The exact sodium
concentration was not required for the experiment
since the measurement was performed relative to the
elastic scattering cross section.
The proton transfer experiment was performed at
TUNL using the Enge split-pole spectrograph. The
instrument is located at the end of the
high-resolution beam line at the TUNL Tandem
accelerator laboratory, where two 90-degree dipole
analyzing magnets deliver beams of precisely
controlled energies to the target. A 3He++ beam
energy of 21 MeV was chosen to minimize the presence
of contaminants in spectral areas. The NaBr targets
were placed on a target ladder along with a natural
carbon backing foil for background identification.
The beam current was monitored with an
electron-suppressed beam stop downstream from the
targets. A silicon telescope was placed at 45 degree
to monitor target degradation, and beam fluctuations,
and to normalize the data. Reaction products from the
target entered the Enge split-pole spectrograph
through a 1 msr aperture and were momentum-analyzed
with a magnetic field. Deuterons were clearly
identified with a dE vs E cut. These spectra were
internally calibrated using precisely known states in
24Mg.
Over the entire focal plane, most states are in good
agreement with the literature energies with an average
deviation of 1.3-sigma.
